Hosted at Move Co-op in the heart of Dallas TX, The Movement Experience is about presenting a revolutionary approach to movement development, unlike anything seen elsewhere.

During the event, participants will be exposed to concepts such as:

  • Handbalancing - developing handstands from the ground up, covering tools for proper alignment, breathing patterns, support capacity, wrist conditioning and more. Also supporting intermediate and advanced practitioners on their journey towards dynamic sets and one arm handstands.

  • Gymnastics and Bodyweight Strength - the Ido Portal Method applied to bodyweight skills such as front levers, planches and Gymnastics rings strength development as well as the very basics - chin ups, push ups and dips - learn the most well thought out approach in the market, tailored to your level. Get your first chin up/muscle up/one arm chin - with some of the knowledge shared, your journey will be quicker than ever.

  •  Locomotion - Ido Portal's movement language that includes floor flow work with low acrobatics elements, animal locomotion, low gait, inversions, gliding patterns and much more. Locomotion includes 1200 (twelve hundred) elements, it is the most sophisticated flow system taught on the market.

  •  The Corset - building a flexible body armor around the body. A unique and extreme approach to bullet proofing the body while making huge gains in mobility, strength and movement accessibility.

  • Movement Refinement/terminology - creating refined motor control for later implementation into your movement development - if you are interested in achieving an advanced movement practice like one arm handstands, low level quadrupedaling, flips, twists or one arm chin ups - you will need to control small and articulated refined motor actions using certain segments of the body in Isolation. The height of your movement refinement will dictate the height of your movement complexity.

  • Kinetic Koans - confronting movement riddles and learning to approach them while reaping benefits such as movement intelligence and adaptability.


Time:
2 days X 10:00AM-8:00PM (lunch break in the middle)
* Make sure to clear your schedule in this weekend and not book any flights back, important dinners or other obligations as on both days the event might run later than expected - The team is not working 'by the clock' and attempts to share as much knowledge as possible with the participants during the event.

Others:
We recommend packing your own food for lunch as at certain locations getting food might be a problem.
Please make sure to bring with you: a roll of athletic tape, water bottle, watch/timer/stopper watch, notebook & pen and loose fitting clothes suitable for movement.

**Please note the event is led by the Ido Portal team and master trainers - we can not guarantee Ido or other members presence.

Executive Director, Richard Sumner

(972) 598-0949

richard.s@dfwtechnologies.com

Data Science training is aligned with Cloudera Certification

Placement Assistance available for Jobs in Dallas

Course: Data Science  

THIS TRAINING IS A 4 WEEKEND COURSE WITH DAYS BEING BOTH SATURDAY AND SUNDAY FROM 9 A.M. TO 1 P.M. (4 HOURS EACH DAY). YOU ARE REQUIRED TO BRING YOUR LAPTOP WITH YOU. A 64-BIT MACHINE IS THE MINIMUM CONFIGURATION REQUIRED ON EITHER MAC OR PC. 

 

IDEAL REQUIREMENTS FOR JOINING THE COURSE WOULD BE:

  • Some Familiarity with any Scripting Language 
  • Some Experience with Basic Statistical Concepts

 

COURSE DETAILS:

  • Duration: 32 hours over 4 weekends (Sat and Sun)
  • Timings: 9:00 AM to 1:00 PM (4 hours)
  • Fee: $999
  • Location: Dallas
 
 
REFUND POLICY: 100% refund of your money in the event that you would need to cancel up to 48 hours prior to the start of the course. Yes, it's an amazing policy! 
 
HOW TO REGISTER: PURCHASE YOUR TICKET TO RESERVE YOUR SEAT.
A $200 (NON-REFUNDABLE) DEPOSIT CAN ALSO BE GIVEN TO RESERVE YOUR SEAT WITH THE BALANCE BEING PAID IN FULL PRIOR TO THE START OF THE COURSE. TO GIVE A $200 DEPOSIT, PLEASE SEND AN EMAIL TO REQUEST THE SAME.

 

Course Curriculum 

Module 1: Introduction to data science
  • Data Preparation
  • Data Exploration
  • Data Representation
  • Data Discovery
  • Learning fro Data
  • Creating a Data Produce
  • Insight, Deliverance, and Visualization
 
Module 2: Introduction to R
  • Basics of R
  • Install R and RStudio
  • Advanced Data Structure
  • Reading data into R
  • Statistical Graphics
  • R Functions
  • Control Statements
  • Manipulating Strings
  • Probability Distributions
  • Basic Statistics 
  • Exploring and Visualizing data in R
 
Module 3: Machine Learning Algorithms
  • Supervised and Unsupervised Learnings
  • Lazy Learning: Classification Using Nearest Neighbors
  • Probabilistic Learning: Classification Using Naive Bayes
  • Divide and Conquer: Classification Using Decision Trees and Rules
  • Forecasting Numeric Data: Regression Methods
  • Black Box Methods: Neural Networks and Support Vector Machines
  • Finding Patterns: Market Basket Analysis Using Association Rules
  • Finding Groups of Data: Clustering with k-means
  • Evaluation Model Performance 
 
Module 4: Machine Learning Case studies with R
  • Diagnosing breast cancer with the kNN algorithm
  • Filtering mobile phone spam with the naive Bayes algorithm
  • Identifying risky bank loans using C5.0 decision trees
  • Identifying poisonous mushrooms with rule learners
  • Predicting medical expenses using linear regression
  • Identifying frequently purchased groceries with association rules
  • Finding teen market segments using k-means clustering
 
Module 5: Introducing Big Data Hadoop Ecosystem
  • Hadoop distributed file system and MapReduce
  • Solving Problems with MapReduce
  • Introducing Apache Mahout 
 
Prerequisites 
  1. Some familiarity with any scripting language like SQL or R (R will be taught in detail in the class).
  2. Some experience with basic statistical concepts such as probabilities, means, standard deviations and significance.
 
"The course will have extensive in-class lab work and offline assignments"
 

 

FAQ's

 

Q: Will the training be in person or Online?

A: Training's are held in person @ the Park Plaza Tower located in Dallas, TX. The address is 13111 N. Central Expressway and is located at the corner of the high-five interchange. The class will be led by an instructor in person. 


Q: What am I required to bring?

You must bring your laptop and its configuration must be at a minimum a 64-bit machine, being either Mac or PC. 


Q: What is your Refund policy?

A: Life has a way of happening where your plans may need to change. Therefore, DFW offers 100% refund of your money in the event that you would need to cancel. Our policy states that you are given up to 48 hours prior to the start of the course to cancel and then you will be given a full refund. Yes, it's an amazing policy! 


Q: Can I bring a Friend to join me in the course?

A: Most people will bring 1 or more of their friends to join them which also provides a study buddy. Each person part of the course must be a paid student. 

 

Q: Do I get a certificate after the training?

A: A Training Completion Certificate will be provided at the end of the Class for 32 hrs of training and completion of projects. 


Q: Can I ask the instructor a Question?

A: If you would like to talk to the instructor directly about a question related to the course, please either reply to this email or send an email to richard.s@dfwtechnologies.com and provide your name and best contact number. Your information will be passed to the instructor who will reach out to you within a few hours. 

 

Q: Are there online materials available during the training period?

A: Students will be provided study material fo the class and also given online reference materials. Books will be suggested for reading, both online and hard copy.

 

Q: Do you offer placement after the class?

A: Placement is available to those who are looking to switch their careers and is independent of the training's offered at DFW. If you are seeking either contract or direct hire, please email your resume to richard.s@dfwtechnologies.com.

Cross Curricular Writing:   Survival Writing

 

 

 

 

Project-Based Learning (PBL)/Team Teaching

Presenter:          Region 10 ESC

Audience:          Cluster

 

Description

This workshop provides all teachers with strategies, prompts, and practice for expecting good writing in all classes -- not just English Language Arts classes. We begin with common terminology for writing - Across-the-Curriculum so that students and teachers can speak the same language when it comes to writing. We look at summarizing and writing informational texts and practice the one-chunk paragraph for both non text-based and text-based writing.

 

‘Lion Taming 101’ - Classroom Management Skills and Techniques

Presenter:         Richard Crawford, School of Business and Management

Audience:          Cluster and Core (All)

 

Description

This workshop consists of a brief introduction to effective strategies for managing your classroom.   Afterwards, participants and the presenter will exchange of ideas etc. in which all teachers would share some of their own methodologies which work for them. After the session teachers across school and curriculum could find another teacher and through something akin to ‘peer tutoring’ could implement ideas etc. into their repertoire in their individual classes; this later portion would be done on a voluntary basis.

 

Marzano’s Classroom Instruction That Works – Homework and Nonlinguistic Representation

Presenter:         Dina Townsend, Yvonne A. Ewell Townview Center

Audience:           Cluster and Core (All)

 

Description

Classroom Instruction that Works workshop presents an overview of two of the best instructional practices as found in the research literature and then shows how these practices can be implemented in the classroom (Homework and Practice and Summarization).   In this workshop, you will learn these powerful instructional strategies that are generally effective with any student, at any grade level, in any subject area. Specific types of knowledge—such as vocabulary, terms and phrases, details, generalizations, and principles—are applied to instructional practices.

 

GT Foundations Part 1 – Nature and Social/Emotional

Presenter:         Online Workshop

Audience:           Cluster and Core (All)    

 

Description

This is Part 1 of the 30-hour GT Foundations training, required by state law for any teacher serving the needs of gifted students. Gifted education is not for the purpose of singling out children as "elite" or "superior" in any way. Like special education gifted education's purpose is to identify learners with needs that cannot be met in the same way as the general student population. This course is self-paced, which allows you to work at your own pace and at a time that is convenient for you. By choosing this session, you are asking to use the PD time to work on this module in a lab setting.

 

Success on the Advanced Placement English Language and English Literature

Presenter:         Gretchen Polnac, NMSI Consultant

Audience:           Core     

 

Description

English Department will receive training and on close reading, analytical, and writing strategies for student success. This workshop is a MORNING and AFTERNOON training.

 

Response to Intervention (RtI) - EHAA(Regulation) Overview, Roles and Responsibilities Presenter:         Cary K. Jim, Instructional Support Services

Audience:           Cluster and Core (All)

 

Description

This training is OFF CAMPUS at the H.B. Bell Building (room 502). This workshop will review the Dallas ISD Response to Intervention Framework, EHAA (Regulation) and roles/responsibilities of campus staff within RTI implementation. Participants MUST have the approval of their principal AND register for this course on SchoolNet.

 

Scaffolding for Success

Presenter:         TBD

Audience:           Cluster and Core (All)

 

Description

This workshop links assessment, higher-order thinking and a thinking skills framework into an Explicit Instruction process. The design of any assessment piece begins with a task verb, such as ‘explain’, ‘design’, or ‘compare’. The selection of the right verb is crucial as it defines the assessment task, determines how a student will organize their thoughts and research and influences the language they will use.

 

This workshop will focus on a number of thinking tools linked to the various task verbs and offers a practical thinking skills framework for use in the classroom. This workshop emphasizes the need for explicit teaching and the importance of scaffolding tasks with the right thinking tools and the right language, so that all students can succeed.

 

Just in Time -- AP Social Studies: "How to Write"

Presenter:         Peter Evett, Teaching and Learning

Audience:           Core

 

Description

This training is OFF CAMPUS at the H.B. Bell Building (room 502). This two hour professional development for will go over key ideas for making the AP Social Studies experience better for teachers and students. Among the topics to be discussed:

  • Introducing the “How to Write” series. These documents provide easy to use ideas to help students of all experience levels write point-scoring essays. These will also be the focus of the Jan. 9 AP Prep Session.
  • How to design goals for your course
  • Roundtable discussion of your best and favorite 2nd semester ideas. Your chance to share a great resource, cool website, successful lesson plan, or terrific procedure.

Participants MUST have the approval of their principal AND register for this course on SchoolNet.

P25 Interoperability Radio Training

Date:January 22, 2016

Time: 8:00 am -  12:00 pm

Cost: Free, 4 hours TCOLE or TCFT Credit

Instructor: P25 Interoperable Communications Governance Committee

Students should bring a portable radio from their agency if available.

Class Description:The P25 Interoperable Communications Governance Committee presents a training course to introduce common features and programming setting seen with a P25 radio as well as the talk group and channels used for public safety interoperability. By the end of this unit of instruction, the student will have a basic comprehension of P25 subscriber radio features and of the DFW Regional, State, and National Interoperability Talk Groups and Channels available to and used by Public Safety agencies. The student will demonstrate communicating on assigned interoperability talk groups during practical tests using a portable radio.

Target Audience: Public Safety radio users with radios connected to the Fort Worth Regional Radio System and/or DFW Regional Interoperable Talk Groups that may provide mutual aid with other agencies. Public Safety radio users include but not limited to: Local, State, and Federal Law Enforcement Officers, Local and State Fire Fighters, Telecommunicators, Public Works Employees, Local, State, and Federal Emergency Operation Centers, Emergency Medical Services, etc.

Prerequisite Experience of Learners: Basic knowledge of the student’s portable radio features.

Learning Objectives:

A.The student will have a basic understanding of common features of a P25 subscriber radio.

B.The student will be able to define the term “direct interoperability”.

C.The student will be able to identify the Fort Worth IO Call, IO IC, and IO talk groups and their purpose per each interoperability talk group zone (LAW, FIRE, EMS, PW).

D.The student will be able to identify agencies that use the Fort Worth Regional Radio System and who they can communicate with on the interoperability talk groups.

E.The student will be able to have an understanding of the Regional, State, and National Radio Communication Interoperability Systems.


Classroom will not be open before 7:45 a.m. Please enter through the training room entrance, do not enter at the front of the building.

The EMBODI Program of the Metropolitan Dallas Alumnae Chapter of Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc. is hosting a FREE Conference for young males in grades 7th to 12th.

The conference will take place on Saturday, January 30, 2016 9am to 1pm at:

Presbyterian Hospital of Dallas, 8194 Fogeison Dr., Dallas, Texas.

 

The conference will provide invaluable workshops for the young men to participate in across a broad array of topics, including: Racial Profiling, Community/GrassRoots Organizing, Understanding Your Constitutional Rights, Goal Setting & Money Management. The presentors include representatives from the Dallas District Attorney's Office, Dallas Law Enforcement, Financial Advisors, and Community Leaders.

 

 

We encourage parents, counselors, community based organizations, Fraternities and Churches to register their young men to attend this FREE Conference.

This is a FREE community event, however pre-registration is required. The deadline to register is Saturday, January 23, 2016

For more information, please contact us at EMBODI.MDA@GMAIL.COM  

 

Funding for this event was provided in part by The Shirley A. Fridia Development Center, Inc and Mary Kay Cosmetics.

Business taxes are due in March and it’s too late to do anything about 2015, but you can get a head start on 2016 tax planning with tips from three impressive Tarrant County
CPAs. Toni Ciggs of Tom B. Johnson CPA, Susan Roberts of CliftonLarsonAllen and Daniel Stewart of JTaylor will answer your questions about subjects such as the new
regulations of the Affordable Care Act, extenders, overtime pay thresholds, same-sex marriage, changing your business entity and benefits for the self-employed.

Toni Ciggs is a CPA with experience in Public Tax and Industry Accounting. She received her undergraduate Degree in Accounting from the University of Illinois at Chicago and a Master of Science in Taxation from the University of North Texas.  She works as a Tax Manager with the Tom B Johnson, CPA, PC firm in Arlington, where she prepares tax returns for Corporations (C-Corp & S-Corp), Partnerships, Trusts, Estates, Non-Profits, and Individuals.

Principal Susan S. Roberts enhances CLA’s corporate leadership through her extensive knowledge and experience providing customized solutions for manufacturing enterprises and serial entrepreneurs. With a unique ability to assess important aspects of external and internal financial reporting needs---and to gauge their impact on efficiency and productivity---Susan’s agile interaction and absolute attention to detail are invaluable. She has a remarkable depth of understanding of each industry and over 20 years in public accounting, providing a particular penchant for strategic consulting on corporate taxation, entity selection, and multi-state taxation issues.

Daniel Stewart joined JTaylor in June of 2014 as a Manager in the Tax Services Division. He brings more than 10 years of public accounting experience with 8 years focused on non-profit taxation of public charities, private foundation and several different categories of non-charitable tax exempt entities. He also has significant focus in filing applications and documentation to secure federal and state tax exempt status. Other areas of practice for Daniel include manufacturing, oil and gas, professional service industries, real estate, high net worth individuals, fiduciary taxation, and estate and gift taxation.

description:
We can't believe it has been 3 years!  

In the last year, we expanded our brewery & taproom operations, released some super exciting beers, started distributing in Austin - and had a blast while doing it!

One thing is certain- we couldn't have done it without YOU - our family, friends, and loyal supporters!  We hope you'll make it out to celebrate with us.  We'll be tapping rare beers, rocking out to amazing local tunes, eating from our favorite food trucks, and enjoying a craft beer extravaganza!

Come join us, as we throw our best party yet!  

EVENT DETAILS:

Date: Saturday, January 23, 2016
Time:  12:00 - 6:30pm  
Location: at the brewery (1530 Inspiration Drive, Dallas, TX 75207)

  • 30+ BEERS! (beer list will be posted at www.CommunityBeer.com)
  • MULTIPLE Beer Stations
  • LIVE BANDS 
  • Lots of Room (taproom, brewery area, and outside tent)
  • Photo Booth
  • Awesome local Food Trucks
  • Commemorative Special Edition Glassware & T-shirts
  • Local Artists & Craft Vendors

 

TICKET TYPES:

We are capping ticket sales to minimize the crowds, so be sure to grab your tickets early.  
We will not be selling tickets at the door this year.

 

  • PREMIER (Extremely Limited):
    • First Entry @ 12:00pm
    • Limited Edition Anniversary T-shirt
    • Complimentary Food Truck Ticket
    • Commemorative Lanyard
    • Commemorative Special Edition Glass
    • Drink Card for 8 pours (extra sample cards available for purchase)
          
  • EARLY ENTRY (Limited)
    • Early Entry @ 1:30pm
    • Commemorative Special Edition Glass
    • Drink Card for 8 pours (extra sample cards available for purchase)
  • GENERAL ADMISSION 
    • Entry @ 3:00pm
    • Commemorative Special Edition Glass
    • Drink Card for 8 pours (extra sample cards available for purchase)

 

FAQs

When should I get there?
Depends on the ticket you have.  

  • Premier tickets can access at Noon.
  • Early Entry can access at 1:30pm
  • General Admission is at 3:00pm
There will likely be an early line at the door, but we will get everyone in as quickly as possible.  Have your ID and ticket (paper print out or on your phone) ready.  There will be plenty of beer to go around, regardless of ticket type.  Good times all day!

 

Will you be selling tickets at the door like last year?
No, we are offering pre-sale online tickets only.  We did not anticipate the crowds we received last year, so in order to reduce the lines, we are capping online ticket sales and will not be selling tickets at the door.  

Age/ID requirements?
You must be at least 21 years to drink, and show a valid ID.  You will be wrist-banded, and must show this wristband while at the event.  However, children accompanied by a parent can enter.

Do non-drinkers and children have to have a ticket?
All attendees must pay to enter.  The cost helps cover staffing, bands, and extra event expenses.  It'll be worth it though!  The beer samples are included with entry, whether you drink or not.  

The only exception is that children accompanied by a parent can enter for free.  Please keep your children with you at all times!  Ever watch Willie Wonka & the Chocolate Factory?   Just sayin....

What are my transport/parking options?
We have a large (free) parking lot in front of our main entrance.  However, if you'd like to take public transportation, you have some great options.  

The closest DART train stop is in front of the American Airlines Center, which is directly across the highway from us.  But you don't have to dodge cars like Frogger to get across.  A sidewalk will guide you from the train stop, under the Stemmons Freeway bridge (via HiLine), and around the corner to Inspriation Drive where we are located ... roughly a 7 minute walk.

And, we're big supporters of UBER & LYFT.  Always great options.  

*PLEASE NOTE- BACK PARKING LOT WILL BE CLOSED!


What can/can't I bring to the event?
All the obvious stuff.  Just don't be stupid, please.  Definitely no weapons, drugs or other alcohol products. Nothing that ruins other people's good times.  We don't want the negative vibe of having to have a cop throw you out.   Nobody wants to be that guy.  

You can also bring folding chairs, as there will be limited seating.


Do I have to bring my printed ticket to the event?
Having your ticket pulled up on your phone is the easiest and greenest option.  Tickets are great, especially for back-up purposes.  We also have an order list at the desk.  Either way, having your ticket on your phone will ensure everyone gets in as quickly as humanly possible! 

The name on the registration/ticket doesn't match the attendee. Is that okay?
Depends.  We've seen all the tricks.  But seriously, that's cool as long as the purchaser name lines up on our records.   Having your ticket or confirmation on your phone is highly recommended.

Dog friendly?
We are definitely usually dog friendly.  Our 3 Year Anniversary is no exception.  However, we'll have a large crowd and sometimes leaving the dog at home is a good idea.  All dogs must be on leash, potty-trained, extremely well-behaved, and good with both people and other dogs.  

How do the beer samples work?
Your entry fee gets you a sample card for eight (8) samples.  Each sample is roughly 6 ounces.  Some higher ABV and specialty beers may be less.  If you are drinking responsibly, extra sample cards can be purchased.  

What about food?
Highly recommended!  Definitely eat while you are here sampling beer.  We will have a few food trucks (and a dessert one too) on site.  Save your appetite for these guys.  Delicious!

Purpose of the Course

The Trainers EDGE replaces the Trainer Development Conference (BSA 500) as the required train‐the‐ trainer course for Wood Badge and NYLT staffs. The purpose of the Trainers EDGE course is to provide and help develop the platform skills of a trainer. It is meant to supplement the practice offered through Wood Badge and NYLT staff development, with a focus on the participant, while raising the level of skill a trainer brings to the staff experience. Only practice can polish these skills, but this course is intended to “train the trainer” on behaviors and resources while offering hands‐on experience in methods and media. 

Participants should prepare a presentation (about five-to-ten minute duration) before the course and bring the material, equipment, and/or props they need to deliver the presentation.  (NOTE:  Space will be limited)  They will be given an opportunity to practice this presentation in a small group setting and receive feedback.  The topic of the presentation is at the discretion of the presenter, Scouting topics/skills are always good. Additionally, participants will prepare a second presentation during the course, practice it with their small group and receive feedback.

The course is designed for individuals who will be delivering training to adults and youth leaders in all parts of the Scouting program:

About Workforce Live

Get your brain buzzing on ideas besides coffee. Workforce Live is our speaker series that provides human resource professionals a strong shot of thought leadership, practical tips, inspiring stories and industry specific research from our Business Intelligence Board — all before lunchtime. The live events begin bright and early and feature a total of eight speakers who deliver their remarks in a fast-moving, TED-talk style. The 18-minute presentations are given by local experts, practitioners and scholars. And the format of the morning event allows for professional networking with peers in your region. Workforce Live will stop in Boston, Washington, D.C., New York, San Francisco, Chicago and Dallas.

Workforce Live will address a wide range of people management matters, such as big data at work; employee engagement; talent acquisition; benefits and wellness; and flexible work policies. Our past speakers have included: Davey Nickels, people analytics manager at Google; Maureen McDonald, executive director of human resources at Dell; and Sidney Chapon, senior vice president of people and operations at Leo Burnett.

Each Workforce Live event will feature a custom research presentation based upon data collected by the Workforce magazine Business Intelligence Board on workplace innovation and culture. Attendees will receive a complimentary whitepaper that explores one of the most common ways to foster both innovation and culture change within organizations.

description:
Practical Applications of Digital Radiology in Dental Practice - Friday, February 26, 2016

Course Summary:

Advances in digital radiological imaging have created an ideal opportunity to simplify the diagnostic and treatment planning process, and to improve clinical outcomes. Dental treatment in the new millennium has progressed to a higher level because of new technology and systems. But, what system is right for you? The challenge for any dentist is to understand the clinical problems and to determine the proper method of treatment. This course is designed to provide the practitioner with the latest in practical applications of digital radiology, with a special emphasis on what works and what systems are currently available. This course will primarily be a lecture course however small group discussions will provide additional interest and learning.

Course Presenter:
Dr. Byron “Pete” Benson Is a 1975 graduate of University of Iowa College of Dentistry and serves as professor and vice chair in the Department of Diagnostic Sciences at Baylor College of Dentistry, as well as director of Radiology/Imaging Center. He received a certificate in Dental Diagnostic Science from UT-San Antonio in 1986 and attained diplomate status with the American Board of Oral and Maxillofacial Radiology in 1989. He is also a diplomate of the American Board of Oral Medicine. He has received numerous awards and professional recognitions and has published over 100 text chapters, journal articles and abstracts in various scientific publications. Dr. Benson has become an expert in the area of digital radiology over the past several years and has presented this program to numerous dental conventions and meetings throughout the country. The teaching methods will include lecture and radiographic case review with participant discussion.

Disclosure of commerial relationships:   Dr. Bensen is a consultant for Gendex, Soredex, PaloDex and has had speaker support from Dentsply, Imaging Science International.  He works with cosigned equipment from PaloDex, Planmeca and Practice Works/Kodak.  There is no corporate funding for his CE program at Baylor and no conflict of interest regarding the relevant information presented in his program.

Course Information:

Date: Friday, February 26, 2016

Time: 

  • 8:00 am - 8:30 am – Registration
  • 8:30 am - 4:30 pm – Presentation

Location: Baylor College of Dentistry, 6th Floor

Credit: 7 hours lecture and small group discussion

Course Pre-requisites:  It is recommended that the attendee have experience with digital radiology however the dentist and staff initially implementing digital radiology in the dental practice is invited to attend.  Recommended for dentists, specialists, dental assistants, and dental hygienists.  This course is designated for CDE credits and is not promotional in any way.

Course Fee: $275 Dentists; $155 RDH or Aux.

AGD Codes:165 Digital Radiology; 562 Digital/Video Imaging; 730 Oral Medicine, Oral Diagnosis; 731 Radiology

Continental breakfast and lunch provided

Course Topics and Objectives:

History and basic features of digital radiology systems

· Radiology of caries, periodontal and periapical disease

· Two dimensional and three dimensional digital imaging

· Vendor review of digital radiology software programs

· How to capture images, display and use them effectively

· Problem-solving & clinical applications

· Future developments in digital radiology

description:
VECTORWORKS CORE CONCEPTS TRAINING

Tuesday, January 5 – Wednesday, January 6


COURSE DESCRIPTION

This is the best hands-on training option to learn how to utilize tools, menu commands, and drawing organization found in Vectorworks software. Core Concepts starts from the ground up, teaching you all of the necessary basics needed to become a Vectorworks pro. Make use of 2D and 3D modeling techniques from the start and learn the entry points and correct workflows to help master the Vectorworks platform.
 

OVERALL LEARNING GOALS

Drawing fast, keeping accurate, incorporating easy-to-use drawing structures, employing modern Vectorworks techniques and concepts.

View the list of topics covered.
 

PREREQUISITES 

Those considering classroom training must understand basic drafting concepts, such as plan and elevation projections, scale and actual size, and drawing units. Attendees must also be comfortable with operating either a Macintosh or Windows computer system, as well as understand basic mouse operations such as single click, double click, click and drag, scroll wheel, right click, and two click operations. Attendees would also need to know basic keyboarding, including use of the Spacebar, Tab, Control, Alt, Shift, Delete, Command (Mac), and Option (Mac) keys.

 

 

VECTORWORKS INTERMEDIATE CONCEPTS TRAINING

Thursday, January 7 - Friday, January 8

 

COURSE DESCRIPTION

Take your Vectorworks knowledge to the next level! The Intermediate Concepts course is the best hand-on training option to help you become proficient with information modeling and integrating 2D drafting skills with 3D modeling. Learn how to extract data from any object and list the information automatically in a worksheet. Improve your workflow and graphic output of your construction documents and presentation renderings. Also, learn more about layer and class organization, as well as advanced techniques with viewports and section viewports.
 

OVERALL LEARNING GOALS

To employ Vectorworks conventions and concepts to incorporate the next level of information modeling into each phase of your design workflow.

View the list of topics covered.

 

PREREQUISITES

To qualify for Intermediate Concepts classroom training, candidates must have completed the Core Concepts class within the last two years or understand all of the following topics listed below. If you feel that you do not understand one or more of the topics, we strongly recommend that you take the Core Concepts training class first, as time will not be available to cover these Core Concepts in the Intermediate class.

Attendees must know basic 2D and 3D drawing navigation (e.g., panning, standard views, 3D Flyover tool, and zooming in and out), selecting, moving and resizing objects, as well as standard tool behavior (e.g., single click, two click, three click, and continuous clicking tools). Additionally, this training requires understanding, creating, and editing surface objects, as well as editing container objects such as symbols, plug-in objects, and viewport annotations.

Intermediate students must also be familiar with basic CAD layout methods such as layer scale, smart cursor cues, duplicate array, mirroring, offset and aligning objects, conventions of snaps, and X, Y and Z coordinates. Also required is a knowledge of drawing organization structures such as layers, classes, sheet layers and viewports, along with understanding the purpose of the following Vectorworks software palettes: Object Info palette, Basic palette, Attributes palette, Resource Browser, View bar, and the use of the heads-up display (i.e., floating data display bar).


ADDITIONAL INFORMATION

Windows machines preloaded with Vectorworks 2016 software will be provided for each classroom training attendee. Workshop participants who would like to work on their own machine are required to bring their own laptop or desktop computer with the software installed. The software may either be your own registered license, or you may obtain and install a functional 30-day evaluation copy prior to arriving for the course. We will not issue refunds due to malfunctions of software installed on personal laptops. The course instructor is not available or responsible to troubleshoot or service personal laptops, nor is the trainer responsible for technical problems experienced during the course due to personal computer hardware or software malfunctions. Detailed information on how to download the software will be emailed to you and can be found in your registration confirmation. 

 

MEET THE TRAINER

Donald Ward is a Vectorworks expert and lead trainer at Vectorworks, Inc. He has been with Vectorworks for ten years, initially as a senior technical support specialist working directly with Vectorworks customers. Since 2007, he has been conducting Vectorworks classroom and online training courses at all levels. He has also presented at numerous industry events including LDI and ASLA annual conventions. In addition, Don supports the company’s U.S. sales and marketing initiatives by working with the user group community and by providing customized, on-site team training for Vectorworks clients.

Optimized Living Institute

1858 E. Keller Pkwy, Suite C || Keller, TX 76248

Wednesday, January 6th at 6 P.M.


Let's discover the WHY...

Have you noticed the traditional "shotgun" approach to dieting & exercise doesn't work well for PCOS? Find out why.

Do you know which specific hormone imbalances in particular can be a concern with PCOS?

Have you tried “counting calories” but does not work for PCOS hormonally-driven belly fat?


Let's talk about HOW to make change a reality...

Let's talk about some practical guides on correcting sleep cycles, avoiding sugar cravings, & how to burn fat effectively.

Let's get down to business & create a timeline for expected hormonal change through lifestyle modification.

 


  

  Presented by local anatomy & physiology professor,

Dr. Rebekah Bruner, D.C.

Please R.S.V.P. to (817) 431-9911

Supportive, encouraging guests are welcome. Seating is limited.

Dr. Rebekah Bruner, D.C.


About Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS):

According to Women's Health, "Between 1 in 10 & 1 in 20 women of childbearing age has PCOS. As many as 5 million women in the United States may be affected. It can occur in girls as young as 11 years old."

 

Common PCOS complaints: excessive hair growth, acne, weight gain, blood sugar dysregulation, fertility concerns, pelvic pain, as well as anxiety & depression.

ABOUT Optimized Living Institute:

At Optimized Living Institute we take a natural approach to living a holistic life.

We combine the latest education in functional nutrition, functional neurology, blood work, digital x-rays, & chiropractic care to truly understand your unique physiology & how to best support your life. We understand that no two people are the same and their care plans should reflect that.

We believe in empowering our practice members to be their own healthcare advocates through education, lifestyle modification, and the necessary healthcare resources.

This event is for anyone over 18 years old who is able to make their own healthcare decisions. If not, please bring a spouse or your healthcare advocate with you to this event.

description:
Coaching Agile Teams 3.0: An Integral Approach to Working with Agile Teams in Complex Environments


Coaching Agile Teams is a three day workshop for experienced Agilists who wish to dramatically increase their overall agile coaching skills and effectiveness. Our latest version, Coaching Agile Teams 3.0, is updated and expanded to address the complex environments in which most Agile teams (and Agile Coaches) operate. When we started teaching Coaching Agile Teams in 2010, the main job of most ScrumMasters and Agile Coaches was to get teams up and running well. Now, Agile teams are almost the norm, although many are not running well. And, if they are, they can easily be held back by the broader organizational landscape that is not as “agile-enabling” as needed. Coaching Agile Teams 3.0 addresses this complexity head-on with expanded lessons in:


  • ways to see the broader organizational environment more completely, and tools to work with it

  • role complexity, including the role of managers and roles in a scaled agile setting

  • team culture and evolution

  • working with the impact of organizational culture

  • the Integral Agile Operating System™ that provides a set of thinking tools and a model for crafting powerful agile coaching interventions

The course still delivers the key agile coaching content, skills and mindsets, all built on a transformational education platform that over 2,000 students have already enjoyed. To say the least, it is highly interactive and experiential: we have never had anyone complain of being bored! To say the most, many students have reported that this course changed their work and even their life.


Who Would Benefit from the Class

  • Experienced ScrumMasters, Agile Project Managers or Iteration Managers who want a fuller understanding of the complete range of agile coaching skills.

  • Agile Coaches who want to expand their skill set and gain the ability to break-through previously intractable problems on their teams.

  • Agile managers, Product Owners and others wishing to access a broader range of skills in working with their teams


Prerequisites

This is decidedly not a beginning agile class, but also not an advanced one. It is an intermediate course for practitioners with at least 6 months of hands-on agile experience. You should also be grounded in Agile Fundamentals (ICAgile Certified Professional), a Certified ScrumMaster, or equivalent agile training. The course builds directly on your agile team experience – without this, you and your colleagues will get a less than fulfilling experience. The class prepares you to act as a leader on agile teams and leave with ideas for helping them as soon as you get back.


Outcomes the Class Will Produce

  • While mastering agile coaching skills will require both time and practice, our class will allow you to:

  • Understand and utilize the four key Skill Areas and four Knowledge Areas applied by the best agile coaches (ACI’s Agile Coaching Competency Framework).

  • Create healthy teams that are resilient, creative, resourceful and resonant.

  • Listen fully and ask essential, powerful questions that open up new possibilities and propel people into action.

  • Clearly ascertain the distinction between coaching and mentoring and know when to apply each most successfully.

  • Observe two professional coaching and mentoring demos (live) using students’ real-life agile situations.

  • Understand how to address the dysfunctional approaches to conflict teams often develop.

  • Coach and mentor people through all kinds of change, especially the change required to occupy agile roles fully.

  • See the broader organizational context more clearly and determine the best interventions, and your best actions, to positively affect it. (ACI’s Integral Agile Operating System™)

  • You’ll walk away from the course with your personal coaching improvement backlog – a tangible plan you can use to thoughtfully improve your coaching when you’re back on the job.

You’ll have many new things to try with your teams and you will probably depart with a few provocative ideas to chew on (in fact, maybe wrangle with for a while). All of these outcomes add up to your ability to become the excellent agile coach your teams and organization needs. In addition, the class yields.

  • ICAgile Certified Professional-Agile Coaching (ICP-AC) continuing education certification. (Nominal fee applies)

  • 21 Scrum Alliance SEUs toward the Certified Scrum Professional (CSP) level.

  • 21 PMI PDUs.


Topics

Coaching Agile Teams is a training experience that covers both the being and the doing of agile coaching. There’s a lot to learn, experience and practice! At the end of the course, you will be capable of applying many new tools and techniques, as well as your own mindset changes, to coach agile teams to health. As practical as it is provocative, the Coaching Agile Teams course challenges agile coaches to rise to the fullest expression of their role. Topics include:

  • Professional Coaching. Learn and practice the key professional coaching skills and know when to use them.

  • Mentoring. Practice offering your knowledge and sharing your experience while keeping accountability for taking action where it belongs -- with the person who has the problem.

  • Teaching. Utilize insights from adult learning to amplify your teaching, whether it’s teaching the agile basics or teaching an advanced agile technique.

  • Facilitating. Experience many facilitation techniques you can use with your teams and emulate the expert modeling offered throughout the class.

  • Resonant “WE” Space. Understand team culture and relationships, the evolution of team development, how to move teams toward health and high performance, and practice designing a team start-up or reset.

  • Change and Roles. Articulate the key role transitions for project managers, testers, tech leads and managers and understand how to help people change, specifically related to their agile role transition. Prepare yourself to conduct a pivotal conversation.

  • Roles at Scale. Get clear about how roles operate at scale, what each role needs to focus on, and how they interconnect.

  • Integral Agile Operating System™. Create an assessment of team health and performance using all perspectives through the Integral Agile Operating System™ and determine ways you can actively work with what you discover.

  • Conflict. Change your relationship with conflict and help the team learn to do conflict well, rather than you mediating it or fixing it.

  • Designing Coaching/Mentoring Relationships. Learn how to consciously “design” coaching/mentoring relationships that allow you to operate with both backbone and heart.

  • Coaching Stance. Craft your personal coaching stance, a powerful “come from” place that helps bring your vision of “agile done well” into being.


Foundational Models

  • Agile Coaching Learning Objectives (housed at ICAgile.com)

  • Select ICF Professional Coach Competencies

  • ACI’s Agile Coaching Competency Model

  • ACI's Integral Agile Operating System™


Certifications

  • Coaching Agile Teams is accredited by the International Consortium for Agile (ICAgile) as fulfilling all Learning Objectives in the Agile Coaching track. After successful completion of Coaching Agile Teams, you can apply for the ICAgile Certified Professional-Agile Coaching (ICP-AC). This continuing education certification is a key step toward achieving the ICAgile Expert-Agile Coaching (ICE-AC), the industry's first competence-based certification. (Nominal additional fee to obtain the ICP-AC applies) To be eligible for the ICP-AC, you must not miss more than 1 hour of class. Learn more at ICAgile.

  • Coaching Agile Teams is also approved by the Scrum Alliance and yields 21 SEUs toward your Certified Scrum Professional (CSP) or to support your existing Scrum Alliance certifications, such as the CSM. Learn more at the Scrum Alliance.

  • Any learning in Agile is typically acceptable to the Project Management Institute as continuing education. Coaching Agile Teams yields 21 PDUs that you can claim toward your PMI-ACP or to support your existing PMI certifications, such as the PMP. Learn more at the PMI.

Logistics

Length: Three days

hours: 9 am to 5 pm each day with a lunch break. Cost (North American locations): $2,050. This includes all class materials, morning or noon meal, and snacks. Of that amount, $150 is a non refundable (but transferable) deposit. When you register 5 weeks or more prior to class, a $200 discount may be taken. Cost (Europe, Asia, others): Please contact us for pricing in other locations.

The New Income Alternative

   If you are not familiar with BDCs, then you should join us for an informative CPA CPE Lunch and Learn on Wednesday, January 20, 2016, 11:30-1:00, Texas Star Golf Club, 1400 Texas Star Pkwy, Euless, TX.  Enjoy an excellent luncheon and 1 hour of CPE credit while learning how the Dodd-Frank Act has reduced liquidity for businesses and increased the importance of the BDC.  

   Congress created the BDC in 1980 through an amendment to the Investment Company Act of 1940 to help private U.S. companies raise money. BDCs have become an increasingly meaningful source of capital to help finance and grow private American businesses — and in the process have potentially created jobs and helped fuel the growth of the American economy.  

   BDCs have provided a way for investors to diversify their fixed income portfolio for a rising interest rate environment and a defensive investment approach focused on long-term performance and principal protection.

Education as a Human Right

Sign-up for internet access to the webinar and gather a group.

We have 20 spots for internet access.

Join us at TCU for the Webinar on a big screen and lunch.

We have 65 seats for lunch and the webinar on TCU's campus.

Journey for Justice Alliance

The webinar will lift the voices of the people directly impacted by public education policy--students, parents and educators--to examine how corporate education interventions impindge on their human right to education. The Journey for Justice Alliance (J4J), a national network of 39 community organizations in 23 cities across the United States committed to community-driven school improvement, will facilitate the webinar. J4J members believe, through their lived experience and research, that a lack of equity is the primary problem in public education. The lack of equity in public education is a civil and human rights issue.


Liberation Lunch Webinar

The webinar will focus on school privatization in cities like Chicago, New Orleans, New York and Detroit through  lived experience: over-reliance on standardized test, punitive school interventions, zero tolerance discipline policies, ignoring community wisdom and the attack on teachers of color, massive school closings, and the expansion of charter and contract schools. This session will be facilitated by the National Director of the Journey for Justice Alliance, Jitu Brown.

description:
Numerous Resources… One Location!

What is the “Best Southwest Everything Teen Expo 2016”?

ETE is a Best Southwest collaborative Teen Expo in partnership with the DeSoto, Cedar Hill, Duncanville and Lancaster Public Libraries driven, planned and organized largely by teenagers.

 

 

Where will it be held?

DeSoto Town Center

211 E. Pleasant Run Road Suite C.

DeSoto, Texas 75115

 

 

When will it be held?

Saturday, April 02, 2016 from 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.

 

 

How much does it cost to attend?

There is no charge to attend the event. There is a charge for vendors.

 

 

What is the vision of ETE?

To enrich the lives of teens by connecting them with community, resources, services, and support.

 

 

What is the overall goal of ETE?

Our goal is for teenagers to build and sustain meaningful and positive relationships with their community by connecting them with businesses, non-profits, colleges, government institutions, and other organizations both local and nationwide through fun and engaging interactions. This Expo will allow teens to connect with professionals while learning about valuable resources and services that can help them pursue their passion, find their purpose, succeed and overcome obstacles in their lives. 

Why is there a need for ETE?

  • There is a real disconnect between teens and the community.

  • ETE can help organizations have a stronger connection with teenagers.

  • ETE can help organizations that may be underutilizing their resources for teens.

  • ETE can help organizations promote resources and services that would help teenagers.

  • ETE can help organizations tap into the hard to reach teen demographic.

  • ETE can help organizations show that they care about teenagers and the community.

  • ETE can help organizations recruit teens as volunteers, interns or for employment.

     

     

What makes this expo different from other teen events?

This will be the first time that the Best Southwest area will work cooperatively to bring resources and services chosen by and catered especially for teenagers to one place to make them easily accessible. Library staff will team up with teens from area high schools and/or organizations to work together to recruit local and national organizations, teen volunteers, school administrators, community leaders, local government and community members to participate in the event.

 

 

What’s in it for teens?

  • Access to numerous resources and information on topics that interests them.

  • Meaningful lasting connections with great organizations and professionals.

  • Inspiration from motivational speakers, entrepreneurs, and people doing what they hope to do in the future.

  • Interactive games and activities.

  • Community Service Hours.

  • Food, fun, and live entertainment.

 

 

Is this a teen only event?

No. This event is not only for teens but for anyone who works with teenagers, parents, guardians, school administrators, and community leaders. We also encourage family, friends, and even the young at heart to attend.  We want the community to show up in a big way to show their support.

 

 

What will vendors and organizations do at the event?

Vendors will be at their table engaging with teens, walking around engaging with teens, and participating in great games and activities with teens! Basically you will be having fun spreading your information while connecting with teenagers.

 

 

Can organizations participate if they don’t cater to teens?

Absolutely.  This event is not only about connecting teens to great resources and services but also about connecting them with the great people working at your organization. Whether you cater to teens or not, you’re invited to come help us create new connections. We encourage organizations of all shapes and sizes to reserve a vendor table and tell their stories. Whether you’re an electrician, mortgage broker, real estate agent, musician, lawyer, doctor, restaurant owner, or WHATEVER, this event is about connecting teens with people from all walks of life. They will want to learn more about what you do.  

 

 

What can you do to help?

  • ETE needs motivational speakers and presenters.

Presentations should be no more than 15 minutes, be interactive, and engaging.

 

  • ETE needs sponsors.

Sponsorship Opportunities

Become a sponsor at ETE. This is a large undertaking and sponsors play a critical role in making it successful. The Desoto Public Library has 175,000 customer visits per year. The combined total customer visits between all participating libraries is 532,000. Your sponsorship will be viewed by a considerable number of people in the community. We have provided several levels of sponsorships for you to choose from (choose one or a few):

 

Official Title Sponsor   $5,000(2 featured sponsors)

Help us reach our goal of giving out $20K in scholarships to teens who actively participate in planning ETE for college and career training. Become one of 2 Official Title Sponsors who will have their company’s logo prominently displayed on promotional bags given to each attendee at the Expo. Attendees become walking billboards for their company throughout the program. Inserting their marketing collateral into the promotional bags is an opportunity to ensure the maximum number of attendees receives their information on their business.

  • Company name of Official Title Sponsor of the Everything Teen Expo to be read and announced as follows, “Best Southwest Everything Teen Expo 2016 presented by ABC & XYZ Companies”.

  • Company name and logo prominently on front of promotional bag and included on all marketing advertisements.

  • Company flyers or handbills distributed in promotional bags at Information Booth.

    • Exclusive press release sent announcing company’s sponsorship of ETE.

  • Company name and logo on press releases, radio announcements, television and print advertisement.

  • Company name and logo featured in Library email blast newsletter reaching 19,000 customers.

  • Company name and logo printed on Official Expo Guide.

    • Company promoted as a sponsor on the Desoto, Cedar Hill, Duncanville, Lancaster Public Libraries’ websites.

  • Hyper-Link exchange between sponsor & ETE website featured on all participating library websites.

    • Exhibitor space (near entrance location).

    • Right to use event name in all marketing campaigns.

 

Official Area Sponsor   $2,500(6 highlighted sponsors)

Help us reach our goal of giving out $20K in scholarships to teens who actively participate in planning ETE for college and career training. Become one of 6 Official Area Sponsors.  

  • Section of the expo named after your company.

  • Company logo prominently displayed in the section of the expo.

  • Company name and logo included on promotional bag and included on all marketing advertisements.

  • Company name and logo on press releases.

    • Hyper-Link exchange between sponsor & ETE website featured on all participating library websites.

    • Company name and logo printed on Official Expo Guide.

  • Company name and logo featured in Library email blast newsletter reaching 19,000 customers.

  • Company promoted as a sponsor on the Desoto, Cedar Hill, Duncanville, Lancaster Public Libraries’ websites.

  • Exhibitor Space.

    • Right to use event name in all marketing campaigns.

     


Marketing Sponsor   $100 - 500(promotional sponsors)

Market your organization by co-branding with us on our giveaways.

  • $500 sponsorship

      • Company name and logo included on banner and all marketing advertisements.

      • Company name and logo featured in Library email blast newsletter reaching 19,000 customers.

      • Company promoted as Marketing Sponsor on the Desoto, Cedar Hill, Duncanville, Lancaster Public Libraries’ websites.

         

  • $100 - $400 sponsorship

      • Company name included on all marketing advertisements.

      • Company name and logo featured in Library email blast newsletter reaching 19,000 customers.

      • Company promoted as a Marketing Sponsor on the Desoto, Cedar Hill, Duncanville, Lancaster Public Libraries’ websites.

         

         

Giveaway Sponsor   $20 - $25 gift card etc.

To encourage engagement and interaction, we plan to give out a number of small awards for participating in various planned activities and games. Donate any items that you believe would be great for this.

  • Company name and logo featured in Library email blast newsletter reaching 19,000 customers.

  • Company promoted as a sponsor on the Desoto, Cedar Hill, Duncanville, Lancaster Public Libraries’ websites as a giveaway sponsor.

 

 Connecting Sponsor  

Help us create ongoing meaningful connections with teenagers by offering internships, employment, and other great opportunities our attendees can take part in after ETE.

  • Company promoted as a sponsor on the Desoto, Cedar Hill, Duncanville, Lancaster Public Libraries’websitesas a Connecting Sponsor.

 

 

 

How much is a vendor table at ETE?

Businesses can reserve a vendor table and 2 chairs at the event for $100. Vendor tables are free for non-profits with 501c3 (must provide 501c3 determination letter or valid proof).

Welcome to the Raja Yoga Meditation course.

 

Learn Raja Yoga Meditation

 

Raja Yoga is an ancient system of meditation and spiritual understanding. It enables us to return to a state of inner peace, personal power and self-worth through re-kindling the soul's original qualities and virtues.  It provides many answers to age-old questions relating to our identity and purpose and opens up a pathway to true peace of mind and a natural state of happiness. At its deepest level, Raja Yoga Meditation is taught as a method of self-awareness, leading ultimately to self-realization.

 

Benefits of Raja Yoga Meditation

 

Peace of mind; relaxation of body, mind and spirit; new attitudes and responses to life; positive relationships; a deep sense of self-worth; greater concentration and clarity; a clearer sense of purpose and inner stability and contentment.

 

Course Dates:

Lesson 1: Mon, Jan 4th from 7:00pm - 8:30pm,

Lesson 2: Wed, Jan 6th from 7:00pm-8:30pm, 

Lesson 3: Mon, Jan11th from 7:00pm-8:30pm,

Lesson 4: Wed, Jan 13th from 7:00pm - 8:30pm

 

This course introduces the following:

  • Understanding & improving thought patterns by knowing the self
  • Meditation to detach yourself/your mind from negative influences and recharging your inner self
  • Drawing strength from the Supreme Source
  • Understanding the law of cause and effect
  • Developing inner powers

 

What is the mind?

What is peace?

Where can we get peace?

 

Please try to arrive around 6:45pm on the first day and 7pm thereafter, so that you have time to register.

FAQs:

- Postures involved? As this is a meditation course, you will not be required to sit in any posture (as is with hatha yoga)

- Dress? Your dress would best be loose and fully covering your body.

- Do I need to bring anything?A notebook to take notes.

- Any charge No, our activities are free of charge as a community service, voluntary contributions welcome.

-What can I begin to do before the course? For a better experience of the course and meditation, a vegetarian diet without onion,garlic and any addictive substances including alcohol, is recommended.

How Much is my Business worth? How can I increase its Value?

Business owners often overlook value creation and value addition in the regular course. As a result, they often end up obtaining a lower price for their business when it is time to sell and exit. In order to maximize their pay-out, it is important for business owners to focus early on, on measures how they can create and enhance the value of their company.

This presentation will familiarize you with some of the most fundamental principles and methodologies of business valuation. This will also highlight the objectives of conducting a valuation, and most commonly used valuation methods that analysts use to assess companies and closely held business entities.

Takeaways:

  • General overview of business valuation.
  • Commonly used valuation methods.
  • Strategies for value creation.
  • Measures to enhance the value for your company.


Presenter

Madhu Ahuja is a CPA with Ahuja & Clark, PLLC, with significant experience in addressing tax issues confronting several industries. In over 17 years of public accounting, Madhu has served diverse clients in the capacity of a federal, state and local tax expert. Madhu has specialized in assisting her clients with federal tax consulting, compliance, taxability studies, voluntary disclosure projects, audit appeals, negotiations/transactional planning consultation, and billing system reviews/implementations.

In addition to being a Certified Public Accountant, Madhu is also a Certified Valuation Analyst and is experienced with business valuations for partner buy-sells, SBA lending, sale of company and estate and gift tax planning.

STAAR Reading and Writing: Best Practices Crash Course

with Gretchen Bernabei

January 13, 2016 in Richardson, TX

8:30am - 2:30pm

 

This workshop will be split between grammar, writing and reading, using materials Gretchen has adapted from STAAR released tests and live student STAAR essays. Specific high-yield strategies covered include:


Grammar:

Nailing fragments and run-ons, using the sentence wringer

Wiping out usage problems ( like its/it’s and there/their/they’re) once and for all

Showing your students how to use their parts-of-speech knowledge

Keeping track of your grammar-teaching-in-context



Reading:

Kernelizing passages for multiple choice ease

Recognizing and using pitchforking in questions

Extracting text structures from passages


Writing:

Generating quick lists and kernel essays 

Choosing from five text structures for expository or persuasive essays

Using icons for developing details

 

 


Participants will receive a copy of "Grammar Keepers."


 

Who is it for? 

Anyone involved in preparing students (grades 4-11) for STAAR writing tests

 

Agenda:
8:00 Registration and coffee
8:30   Quick list to generate topics for expository/persuasive
9:15   Kernel essay #1: five-paragraph essay minus one
9:35   Kernelizing high-scoring essays
9:45   Dialogics in grammar:  your and you’re
10:00 Break
10:15 Kernel essay #2:  evolution of a term
10:40 Additional structures
11:00 Kernelizing reading passages
11:30 Lunch assignment
12:30  11-minute essay
12:50 Specificity in essays using HANNAHs
1:00   Paragraph overhaul
1:45   Deconstructing multiple choice questions in reading and writing
2:00   Putting it all together with icons
2:15   Wrap-up and evaluations

 

Is this the same as Gretchen's previous workshops?

Participants will receive new links to STAAR materials adapted by Gretchen, using the STAAR 2015 released tests from grades 4 and 7, EOC I and EOC II. The basic strategies are the same.

 

What people are saying:

If you want to bring back spark with your spouse, enrich your engagement, or foster skills for a future relationship, come to an Empowering Families workshop!  Empowering Families provides a monthly workshop on healthy relationship skills and positive communication.  Engaged couples who attend the 8 hour workshop together will receive a certificate of completion, which can be used at the County Clerk’s office for a $60 discount on the marriage license.

The cost is $10 per couple, which includes all class materials.

Participants are requested to bring a lunch. 

The workshop will be held at the First United Methodist Church of Hurst (in the Anderson Center) and additional details regarding classroom location/parking/directions will be provided upon registration. 

Childcare is available with preregistration.

Pre-registration is required. Space is limited.

Questions about workshops? Call us at 817-632-5529 or email kemerson@theparentingcenter.org

 All relationships have their ups and downs, but watch out for those red flags! If you are being verbally or physically threatened, constantly feel like you are walking on eggshells, feel powerless, or your friends and family are always concerned, you may be in an unhealthy relationship. These kinds of issues are, unfortunately, very common.  But please note, Empowering Families classes are not designed to help in these circumstances.  For further information or help,  please contact Safe Haven at 877-701-SAFE (7233). If you are in immediate danger, call 9-1-1.

Registrations received by 3pm on the Wednesday prior to the class will have discount certificates available at class. Registrations received after the Wednesdsay prior to the class may not have discount certificates available at class. Any certificates that are not available at class will be mailed to participants the following week.

 Please note: Refunds are not available, although we can re-schedule you in the next available class with advance notice. Participation in the Empowering Families Project is strictly voluntary.  Empowering Families relationship workshops are recognized by:

description:
Nancy A. Vish, RN, PhD, is president and chief nursing officer for the Baylor Jack and Jane Hamilton Heart and Vascular Hospital. Since 2002, Dr. Vish has led north Texas’ first hospital dedicated solely to the care and treatment of heart and vascular disease. Her vision and commitment to quality, patient-centered care have enabled the hospital to become a destination of choice for patients in North Texas, across the state of Texas and from across the nation, seeking diagnosis and treatment for a wide variety of heart and vascular issues. Baylor Hamilton Heart and Vascular Hospital has become one of the leading heart disease research centers in the country thanks to Dr. Vish’s compassion and dedication to bringing tomorrow’s revolutionary cardiac interventions to patients today. Her laser-like focus on collaboration with world renown cardiologists, interventional cardiologists and cardiovascular surgeons on the medical staff of Baylor Hamilton Heart and Vascular Hospital, has resulted in evidence-based care being delivered to every patient, every time. This has led to quality outcomes that consistently place Baylor Hamilton Heart and Vascular Hospital near the top of national quality performance metrics. Thanks to her experience as a nurse and her passion for leadership the hospital has earned many awards and recognitions, including:

  • The Guardian Award for Excellence in Patient Satisfaction and the Beacon of Excellence Award in Patient Satisfaction from Press Ganey

  • Top Performer on Key Quality Measures from The Joint Commission

  • Named one of the “Nation’s Best Cardiovascular Programs” by Becker’s Hospital Review

  • Magnet® status for excellence in nursing services from the American Nurses Credentialing Center

  • Named to Modern Healthcare’s Best Places to Work list in 2012, 2013, 2014 and 2015

  • Texas Award for Performance Excellence, the state’s highest honor for quality and organization performance, from the Quality Texas Foundation

  • 2014 Mission: Lifeline® Gold Achievement award from the American Heart Association for efforts to provide prompt, evidence-based care for heart attack patients.

 

Dr. Vish holds a doctor of nursing degree from Texas Women’s University, a master of science in nursing degree from Vanderbilt University and a bachelor of science in nursing degree from Indiana University of Pennsylvania. Prior to assuming her role as president/CNO for Baylor Hamilton Heart and Vascular Hospital, she was vice president of clinical operations/CNO for the hospital. She has also served as program manager/director for the cardiac cath lab, electrophysiology/PM lab, coronary care unit and interventional cardiology unit at Baylor University Medical Center and as head nurse of the specialty care unit at St. Thomas Hospital in Nashville, TN. She began her nursing career at Presbyterian University Hospital in Pittsburgh, PA.

 

Dr. Vish has received many special honors during her career:

  • Top 100 Women in Healthcare to Watch by Becker’s Hospital Review in 2012, 2013 and 2014

  • Finalist for D Magazine Top Nurses-Administration

  • Nominated to attend Leadership Dallas by the Dallas Chamber of Commerce

  • Profiled by Health Leaders Media

  • Great 100 Nurses of Dallas

 

Dr. Vish is a Fellow in the American College of Healthcare Executives, past president of the American Association of Critical Care Nursing (Dallas chapter), sigma Theta Tau International Nursing Scoiety, Society of Invasive Cardiovascular Professionals, American College of Cardiovascular Administrators Society of Critical Care Medicine, Vascular Nurses Society, American Nurses Association, Texas Nurses Association and Texas Organization of Nurse Executives.

description:
The Faith Community Action Team of the Dallas Coalition for Hunger Solutions joins VNA Meals on Wheels for the 5th annual Martin Luther King (MLK) Day of Caring addressing hunger in our community.

Over 20,000 seniors are food insecure in Dallas County and while VNA helps feeds 4,000 seniors daily, there are many more seniors in need. The faith community can make a difference!

On Monday, January 18th, the MLK Day of Caring will give congregations an opportunity to have an impact on hunger by delivering hot, nutritious meals to homebound seniors, especially in the southern sector of Dallas. And, money is saved so that additional seniors can be served in the future. Our goal is to engage volunteers from the faith community to help cover 100% of the VNA Meals on Wheels routes that day!

How the Day of Caring Works

  • Sign up as an individual or with your congregation.
  • We ask that people go on routes in teams of 2, so groups that have more than 2 will be divided up into multiple routes.
  • You will be notified with detailed information in advance about your route as well as a pick-up time (between 10am-11am).
  • Participants will arrive at the meal distribution location to pick up meals (if there is a change in distribution location we will let you know):

    Concord Church

    6808 Pastor Bailey Drive

    Dallas, TX 75237

    • Each route includes on average 5-10 stops serving an average of 10-12 individuals.
    • You can suggest a preferred neighborhood in southern Dallas County to serve but the ability to accomodate that preference will depend on where meal recipients are located and other factors.
    • Each route takes no more than 2 hours.
    • Participant drivers must hold a valid drivers license. Children under 16 year of age can participate with an accompanying adult.

     

    For questions, please contact VNA’s Kim Peters at 214-689-2210 or petersk@vnatexas.org.

Class Description:  ​This fantastic 24-hour policy workshop is the only communications and 9-1-1 specific policy & procedure workshop offered by any training provider. We are very proud to offer this 24-hour version of our popular Policy Workshop. This class can travel anywhere in the nation. Be aware, this is a true working workshop! A minimum of 2 PSTC Instructors will help you develop your new policy manual or improve your existing Policy and Procedure Manual!

 

Students will leave the class with dozens of policy examples, procedures, and evaluation documents. Most importantly, you will develop a working policy and procedure document template and manual that will be specific to your agency! Students will walk away with a clear understanding on how to write, review and implement policies. There are a variety of reasons or excuses that your agency has for not having a Communications Specific Policy Manual: You're too busy to sit down and write it; You don't have experience writing a document that may someday be used in court or in a termination of an employee; You don't have an example to go by; You don't have a mentor or guide to help you; Your dog ate the one you've been working on; or, You really want some help and ideas. PSTC to the rescue!

 

We know what you need and we're thrilled to be the first dispatch training provider to offer a class to help you!

 

Topics include:

The Importance of Building Policy and Procedure

Wording your Policy

Are You Avoiding or Attracting Liability?

The Nexus between your Policy & Procedure with your Training Manual

Practical Experience

CALEA, IAED and other certification processes and the policy connection

Developing, writing, implementing, training and evaluating policy

Connecting the dots of hiring, training, employee evaluation and the policy manual

Policy versus Procedure

Building Agency Policy into a Communications Specific Policy Document

Avoiding liability and understanding the concepts of "risk management"

 

Practical Exercise – Comparison of two policies, which would you choose and why? The class will discuss and develop a wide range of policies that you need. 9-1-1 Hang-ups, wireless emergencies, citizens following an emergency, missing children, media releases, conduct, attire, tardiness, computer access, training, chain of command, customer service, call priority, supervisory notification and many more. The magic of this class is that you can choose what policies are important to you and we'll show you the benefits and pitfalls of all of your policies.

Then, we show you the procedure side of the house and in no time, you'll have a map for success! Accountability for your new Policy and Procedure Manual. We need a new policy NOW, how do you effectively build it, train it and track it? Resource sharing

 

Additional Information: Students will be welcome to stay after class if they wish individual assistance from PSTC staff. Students will be asked to bring a laptop if possible. Documents we will provide are in Microsoft Word. The class will be configured for networking and interaction. All student seats will have power for your laptops. This is a true workshop. We ask that you bring copies of your current policy manual, your training manual and your employee evaluation forms with you. Bell Helicopter's R&D Strategy" 
     
Guest Presenter:
Vince D'Arienzo

Bell Helicopter Textron
 
Vince will discuss Bell Helicopter's approach with respect to North American Aerospace reduction in R&D funding and lack of skill sets entering today's aerospace industry. He will describe a program format to help focus our industry's R&D effort towards a common pre-competitive approach in the aerospace industry. Some successes will be highlighted  based on Colleges, Government, Industry, and Universities cost sharing and partnering. 
 
Guest Presenter

Vince D'Arienzo
     
Vince D'Arienzo is currently Director, Engineering Operations, at Bell Helicopter Textron.  As such he is responsible for the following areas: Eng design tools [ie: ENOVIA, CATIA, etc], Project Engineering, Systems Eng, Materials & Process Eng and Labs, Manufacturing Research and Development. 

Vince was a Technical Fellow responsible for the health of this discipline and the technology roadmap, ensuring that new technology is being evaluated and developed to a level of readiness for implementation on Bell's helicopters or tilt-rotors.

Vince has worked on many development programs and production support, including the development of new materials with suppliers and other OEMs such as Boeing and Lockheed Martin, such as the present BMI materials used today in most aircraft including our helicopters and the recently developed US jet fighters.

Vince was Chief of Materials & Process group and Labs comprising of engineers and technicians in the fields of metallurgy and non metallic materials. The tasks were for Bell's facilities and internationally: R & D, design, analysis, quality control, production support, supplier integration, sub-contractor support, and customer support.

In his younger years he was a pit mechanic on motorcycle race teams, Yamaha and Honda; which led to design/analysis and manufacture of different components of race motorcycles and cars, including Indy and F1.

Date:January 22, 2016
