Cost: Free, 4 hours TCOLE or TCFT Credit

Instructor: P25 Interoperable Communications Governance Committee

Students should bring a portable radio from their agency if available.

Class Description:The P25 Interoperable Communications Governance Committee presents a training course to introduce common features and programming setting seen with a P25 radio as well as the talk group and channels used for public safety interoperability. By the end of this unit of instruction, the student will have a basic comprehension of P25 subscriber radio features and of the DFW Regional, State, and National Interoperability Talk Groups and Channels available to and used by Public Safety agencies. The student will demonstrate communicating on assigned interoperability talk groups during practical tests using a portable radio.

Target Audience: Public Safety radio users with radios connected to the Fort Worth Regional Radio System and/or DFW Regional Interoperable Talk Groups that may provide mutual aid with other agencies. Public Safety radio users include but not limited to: Local, State, and Federal Law Enforcement Officers, Local and State Fire Fighters, Telecommunicators, Public Works Employees, Local, State, and Federal Emergency Operation Centers, Emergency Medical Services, etc.

Prerequisite Experience of Learners: Basic knowledge of the student’s portable radio features.

Learning Objectives:

A.The student will have a basic understanding of common features of a P25 subscriber radio.

B.The student will be able to define the term “direct interoperability”.

C.The student will be able to identify the Fort Worth IO Call, IO IC, and IO talk groups and their purpose per each interoperability talk group zone (LAW, FIRE, EMS, PW).

D.The student will be able to identify agencies that use the Fort Worth Regional Radio System and who they can communicate with on the interoperability talk groups.

E.The student will be able to have an understanding of the Regional, State, and National Radio Communication Interoperability Systems.

Being a daughter of a dentist and working within the field prior to dental school, Dr. Danette McNew is
a champion for dental education and oral healthcare in the community.

She owns a private practice in Rockwall, Texas and has been practicing solo for 28 years. She also is Associate Clinical Professor at Texas A&M/Baylor College of Dentistry for the past 25 years. She states what has kept her teaching at Baylor for these years and she says, “it is the students who keep her motivated and learning”.

As well, Dr. McNew is active in our local Dallas County Dental Society being a past Chairwoman of the SWDC in 2012, President in 2013-2014 and still continues to be involved with the membership committee. She is on the Board of the Academy for Sports Dentistry and Research Chair for the academy since 2014. Presently she is President Elect for the 2016 year and slated for President in 2017. She is Director for the Athletic Mouthguard Selective at Texas A&M/Baylor College of Dentistry and loves to share her knowledge and sports and dentistry.

description:
Win or lose, a debrief with your client can yield valuable insights into what your firm is doing well and where you need improvement. Getting the conversation isn’t even half the battle, though - to gain the maximum benefit from this golden opportunity, you need to understand how you can get the information you really need, and what you should do with it as you move forward.

This panel discussion features AEC firm leaders who will share insights into their established and successful processes around the debrief interview, such as deciding who will attend and participate, determining what questions will be asked, and how the collected information is then stored, disseminated, and utilized.

Our panel also features representatives from the owner’s side, who will shed light on the debrief from their perspectives and offer insights regarding what consultants should know about the debrief from their seat, and how we can get the most candid, honest, and objective feedback.

The conversation will be moderated by Keyan Zandy, Director of Operations with Skiles Group.

Lunch will be provided.

 

SPEAKERS

Dave Mueller

Perkins+Will

 

  

Dave Mueller has over 25 years of business development and senior management experience in the built environment. He is a Principal and the Regional Director of Practice Development at Perkins+Will, where he has been a driving force in expanding the firm’s Texas practice since he joined in 1997. He was instrumental in the Houston office’s growth from a two-person studio in 2002 to a 30+person office, and he has developed a strategic vision for the Austin, Dallas, and Houston offices that encourages all staff to be client-centric in melding innovation with function.

Dave has specialized expertise in strategic planning in both public and private sectors, and has held executive management position in organizations ranging from international architectural firms to marketing/research consulting firms.

John Carver

Rogers O'Brien

 

  

John Carver, FACHE, is a Senior Vice President for Rogers-O’Brien, where he provides overall strategic leadership to the firm’s healthcare and senior living groups. Following a 27-year career as a hospital executive in senior management positions with Baylor and Methodist Healthcare Systems, John provided administrative direction for a number of major healthcare construction initiatives. This real-world experience makes John a valued development partner, and enables him to bring an owner’s perspective to each and every project that he oversees.

Tom Lund

UT System

 

  

Thomas Lund, AIA, is a ‎Senior Project Manager at UT System, where he and his staff are responsible for overseeing the design and construction of all capital projects on the University of Texas at Dallas campus. Tom manages the selection committees to hire both A/E services and CMAR, CSP, or Design/Build contractors, and he also manages full design phase services, including GMP negotiations and CSP Bid processes.

Tom a practice proven expert in the area of capital project delivery with extensive owner side experience in the design, bidding, construction, and occupancy of state-funded higher education and private sector/commercial properties. His professional experience also includes several years in private practice with two southeast-based regional architectural firms.

Denton Wilson

The Beck Group

 

  

Denton spent the last four years as the Vice President of Design and Construction for Methodist Health System, where he and his team managed all aspects of new clinical construction and renovations. From large ground up facilities to a wide range of specialty projects, he oversaw Methodist's transition from a traditional project delivery approach to a truly collaborative environment as to create best value and a realignment of knowledge.  Denton's teams just successfully completed three $130m complex integrated projects with the last one implementing a RFC "Request for Collaboration" for a project that was an "under build / over-build" with 63 phases.  Denton has overseen over $1.5 billion in healthcare design/construction projects.   

Denton has been in the healthcare architectural/construction environment for more than 28 years with the first 10 on the developer/architectural side of the industry, and the last 18 on the hospital owners’ side. A industry leader and proponent of team integration, his collaboration-based approach gathers, develops, and strives to hold accountable all stakeholder from start to finish including the project- architects, engineers, contractors, trade partners, vendors, and owners. Denton very recently joined The Beck Group, where he serves as the Head of Collaboration across all project sectors.

 

Walk-ins are welcome.

After registration closes you will be responsible for the full cost of the program, even if you cannot make the event. To cancel your registration and receive a refund, please contact Ruth Hunter-Hill at rhunter-hill@purdy-mcguire.com.

During the hands-on portion of the course, students will apply a series of looks on a model and/or on themselves with creative input from instructor. FAQs


What Is The Refund Policy?

Class registration fees are nonrefundable as advance preparations are needed for each class. Prior to registering, please ensure that your schedule allows for you to attend. However, if for any reason the class is cancelled, a full refund will be given to each person. 

Does the class require a certain skill level to attend?

An immediate or advance level of makeup knowledge is required for the hands-on section of the course. No particular skill level is required for the demonstration (Section I). We do require that you maintain a willingness to learn :)

Models are only used for Session II of the course and are not required to purchase a ticket. If your model would like to attend Session I of the course, they would need to purchase a Session I ticket.

Speaker: Chad Williams

Having been a featured guest on a wide variety of television news programs, former U.S. Navy SEAL Chad Williams draws on his experience as a combat veteran SEAL to yield an exclusive perspective rooted in the teachings of Jesus.

Serving his country proudly as a Navy SEAL, on Teams One and Seven, Chad came into contact with the horrors of war first hand, even fighting his way alongside his Team through a premeditated ambush in Iraq.

Today Chad is the author of SEAL of God and an in-demand guest speaker, using the principles and ethos learned as a U.S. Navy SEAL to better communicate the gospel.

 

Band: Shane & Shane

Contemporary Christian Music artists Shane Barnard and Shane Everett, both Texas natives, met shortly after Everett’s Christian conversion when he started attending Barnard’s on-campus Christian fellowship group at Texas A&M University.

As former solo artists, Shane & Shane joined forces in 2001 to create songs of modern worship—singing words saturated in Scripture, exhibiting rich sounds, powerful harmonies, and a clear passion for praising God through their music.

Their debut album, Psalms, released in 2002, peaked at #11 on Billboard’s Christian Music Chart. Shane & Shane broke through to mainstream audiences with the 2004 release of their fourth album, Clean. Their newest release, Psalms, Vol. 2, is directly inspired from the Psalms, pointing listeners to worship and magnify a great God.

Every month (except for January and July), we hold a "Learning" event specifically for new and seasoned real estate investors with the purpose of providing the following:  (1) learning a current real estate topic or strategy, (2) networking with local vendors and (3) hanging out with 150+ like-minded investors.  We are the ONLY real estate club that offers education, networking and DINNER (provided by iDeal Flooring), all for a $5 dollar entry fee (pre-pay). description:
Texas A&M University Singing Cadets were established as an all-male chorus in 1893. The group was originally known as the Texas A&M Glee Club and was renamed the Singing Cadets in 1940.  Texas A&M was originally an all-male, military institution. Therefore, at one time, all of the members of The Singing Cadets were members of the Corps of Cadets. However, Corps of Cadets membership is no longer a requirement for membership in the Singing Cadets.

As well as traveling throughout the state of Texas, the Singing Cadets have also spread the Spirit of Aggieland around the globe. The group has toured to Romania, Mexico, Germany, England, Switzerland, Hungary, Australia, Argentina, Uruguay, and Brazil.  In 1996, invitations to sing in Carnegie Hall and Kennedy Center took the group to New York City and Washington D.C.  St. Paul’s Cathedral and Eaton College were concert sites in May of 1999, and the group revisited the United Kingdom in 2001, visiting Wales, Scotland and England. During the summer of 2006, the Singing Cadets were invited to sing for President George W. Bush at the White House for a ceremony honoring the 2006 Winter Olympics and Paralympics teams. The group also took a trip to Boston and Maine in the summer of 2009 where they sang the National Anthem for the New York Yankees vs. Boston Red Sox game at Fenway Park, performed as a surprise guest for President George Bush’s 85th birthday. In 2010, the Singing Cadets took a country-wide tour of South Africa just before the FIFA World Cup was hosted in the area. The group’s most recent trip took them down the eastern coast of China. Starting in Beijing, the capital, the Singing Cadets performed at each stop through Xi’an, Hangzhou, and Shanghai. The tour provided excellent opportunities for members to embrace a unique culture while representing Texas A&M University across the globe.

description:
DISCOVER THE LATEST IN MATERIAL SCIENCE BREAKTHROUGHS.
LEARN HOW ADVANCES IN TECHNOLOGY ARE ELEVATING PATIENT CARE.
UNDERSTAND HOW CONSUMER DEMANDS ARE AFFECTING TODAY'S PRACTICE.


DIGITAL RESTORATIVE DENTAL SYMPOSIUM

IPS e.max by Ivoclar represents the most significant material science breakthrough in restorative dentistry to date. With equal significance, the tidal wave of advancements in both digital scanning and CAD/CAM technologies just within the last few years have forever changed the dental industry. How? Today, through what is being called digital restorative dentistry, clinicians are able to achieve clinical outcomes that are predictably superior in strength, with the highest level of excellence in esthetics, marginal integrity, fit, and WITHOUT COMPROMISE.

 

SPEAKERS

Dr. Darin O’Bryan graduated in 1997 from the University of Minnesota School of Dentistry. He practiced in Minneapolis for 7 years in a large group practice before moving to the coast of Oregon. Dr. O’Bryan currently resides in Coos Bay/North Bend where he has a private focusing on implant and digital dentistry. Dr. O’Bryan is faculty with CERECdoctors.com at the Scottsdale Center for Dentistry. He is an internationally published author on digital and CAD/CAM dentistry and has mentored thousands of dentists on how to integrate technology into their office. Dr. O’Bryan holds affiliations with the American Dental Association, American Academy of General Dentistry, American Academy of Cosmetic Dentistry and the American Academy of Implant Dentistry. 

 

Dr. Juliani maintains a private practice in Rochester Hills, MI, and is a national educator in the use of dental CAD/CAM technology and practice technology integration. A 1993 graduate of the University of Detroit Mercy School of Dentistry, he completed a one year General Practice Residency, after which he served two years at the United States Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs, CO, where he was the Officer in Charge of Infection Control and Preventative Dentistry. Dr. Juliani has been a CEREC® user since 2003, is a CEREC® basic and advanced trainer, Sirona beta tester, faculty at the Scottsdale Center for Dentistry, and a member of the American Dental Association, Michigan Dental Association, and Academy of General Dentistry. For the fifth consecutive year, he has been listed as one of America’s Top Dentists by the Consumer Research Council of America, and one of Detroit’s Top Dentists by Hour Detroit Magazine.

 

DIGITAL DISCOVERY BREAKOUT

This course is intended for clinicians and team members who have a desire to learn more about the process of digital restorative dentistry. Upon completion of the course, participants will be able to:

  • Describe the differences, advantages and disadvantages between various restorative materials
  • Understand the science and studies of the 10 year clinical success of IPS e.max
  • Identify and describe proper preparation guidelines for the success of IPS e.max press and IPS e.max CAD
  • Identify and describe proper bonding and cementing protocols for the success of IPS e.max press and IPS e.max CAD
  • Evaluate, analyze and comprehend how to take an accurate shade for IPS e.max
  • Identify and describe the restorative workflow of the digital practice through hands-on digital impression scan, margination, restoration design, mill, stain and glaze
  • Understand Integration and Planning of Restoratively Driven Implants
  • Evaluate various case presentations and understand critical keys to success and failure of both lab and chairside restorations
  • Identify, describe and understand the critical aspects and significance of Consumer Marketing, Brand Management and Social Media
  • Much More...


DIGITAL OWNERS BREAKOUT

This course is intended for current owners. Lecture format. Course content to include:

  • 4.4 SW upgrade and Biojaw
  • Milling vs. Grinding
  • Streamline the Digital Dentistry process in your office
  • Custom abutments | Abutment crowns
  • Provisional abutment blocks
  • Anterior and posterior bridge design tips
  • Esthetic anterior restorative tips and tricks
  • Materials and cementation
  • CEREC Guide 2
  • Much More...

DIGITAL ASSISTANT BREAKOUT

This course is intended for assistants. Hands-On course content to include:

  • Designing Tips and Tricks
  • Staining and Glazing Techniques
  • Streamline the Digital Dentistry process in your office
  • Materials Selection
 

8 CE credits after completion of the day course. Early bird registration allows one assistant to register for free when the doctor registers by January 15, 2016.

description:
Guest Speaker:  Kelly Elliott
Director of Diversity Programs, Intel Corporation
 

Topic: 
Technology Security

                                                                                      

 Please forward to anyone interested in this event or in ATW

Join us Thursday, January 14th as we welcome Kelly Elliott, Director of Diversity Programs at Intel Corporation, who will speak on Technology Security.
 
Kelly will share her career journey in technology security and how her observations and learnings led her to contribute significantly to leadership at Intel Security. Kelly led the initiative to co-found the first employee group – Women in Security (WISE) to fill a much needed gap in supporting growth, empowerment and success of women in technology. WISE’s footprint quickly increased 300 % through expansion and engagement increased 50%. The group was quickly recognized as an important component to McAfee/Intel’s diversity initiative and Kelly now leading a newly created team specific to women in security tech at Intel contributes her background in technology roles to bring awareness to this important focus.
 
About Kelly Elliott
Kelly Elliott is Director of Diversity Programs at Intel Corporation. In her current role, she is responsible for driving tighter Diversity & Inclusion (D&I) alignment with champions across business units, creating new retention programs based on growing needs, and helping M&A companies operationalize D&I. Kelly joined Intel from the McAfee (now Intel Security Group) acquisition, where she spent almost 11 years in senior management positions taking on numerous challenges for Technical Support and Human Resources. She started her career at McAfee in 2004 in Support Business Development, where she created a North America sales enablement model and relaunched a global support portfolio, generating over $10M incremental annual revenue. Kelly moved on to lead multi-million dollar global contract negotiations with enterprise customers and partners, earning a seat at the leadership table. She expanded her role driving strategic initiatives, including standardizing the contracting process, purchasing a $1.5M dollar contracting system and overhauling terms and conditions. Her next move was spearheading a customer advocacy program, focused on improving the customer experience for the top 150 accounts. Kelly’s greatest passion was one she personally tackled as an advocate for diversity in the workplace, leading a grass-roots effort to co-found the first employee resource group for women, WISE (Women in Security). Her inspiring leadership was ultimately recognized by McAfee’s President, appointing her to a newly created role in HR to formalize a program, complete with company budget, aimed at recruiting, retaining and engaging women. Kelly joined McAfee with more than 10 years’ experience in high tech companies, including a career start at Lockheed Martin and Sales, Pre-Sales & Professional Services management roles at Sybase and New Era of Networks, start-up companies and SAP consulting.

Kelly holds a B.S. in Business Administration from St. Louis University and holds a Green Belt in Six Sigma Certificate from Villanova University. She’s served 3 years as President/Chair of the WISE board and 2 years on Empowering Women as Leaders (EWL), a non-profit board. Kelly is a member of Catalyst, The Corporate Board and Society for HR Management (SRHM). She was also recently selected as a recipient of the Dallas Business Journal’s 2015 Women in Technology award.  Kelly is based in Plano and resides in the Dallas/Fort Worth area with her husband and two children and loves hiking, yoga and spending time with family. Personally, Kelly is inspired by people who incorporate their passions into their daily lives.

Provides for the management, supervision, and maintenance of the terminal building, runways, grounds, ramps and service roads for Love Field Airport 24 hours a day. In addition, the program provides for the supervision and management of City-owned land and improvements leased to individuals and corporations, as well as operation and maintenance of Dallas Executive Airport in southwest Dallas and the Dallas Public Use Heliport at the Convention Center.

Project Manager/Dept. Representative: TBD
 

City of Dallas Public Works

The Public Works Department is responsible for Capital Improvement Projects funded through voter-approved Bond Programs. From building and replacing sidewalks, street resurfacing and reconstruction, building and remodeling libraries and fire stations, to large-scale projects such as the American Airlines Center, the City Performance Hall, the Winspear Opera House and the Latino Cultural Center, the Public Works Department leads the way!
Project Manager/Dept. Representative: Olugbenro Oyekanmi, P.E.;

Capital Bond Program

Capital Bond Program development and implementation of street, alley, sidewalk, streetscape, and bridge repair projects/Needs Inventory.

City of Dallas Equipment & Building Services

Responsible for City building maintenance, operations, planning, security, and custodial service for approximately 11 million square feet of building space. Facility Management performs operations, maintenance, and repairs of mechanical, electrical, plumbing and roofing systems for approximately 750 Dallas owned or leased facilities. Additionally, Facility Management develops contract specifications and bid documents for procurement to obtain bids and present awards for building repairs/services.  
Project Manager/Dept. Representative: James Davis
 

City of Dallas Water Utilities

Water Operations is responsible for operating and maintaining the facilities of the Water Utilities Department. These activities include the raw water impoundment and watershed management, and the purification, pumping and distribution of potable water. Wastewater Operations is responsible for collecting, transporting, controlling the discharge of, and treating domestic and industrial wastes; and maintaining treatment plants and pipelines in the wastewater system. Capital Improvement Operations plans, designs, constructs and inspects the capital projects needed to provide customers with water and wastewater facilities to meet the growth of the community, extension of water and wastewater mains, modification of facilities to meet changes in State and Federal regulatory requirements (Environmental Protection Agency Administrative Orders, Safe Drinking Water Act treatment parameters and Clean Water Act discharge limitations), and the rehabilitation and replacement of deteriorated or obsolete facilities.
Project Manager/Dept. Representative: Anthony Parker; Project Manager
 

City of Dallas Trinity Watershed Management

Department is divided into four divisions: Flood Control, Floodplain & Drainage Management, Stormwater Management, and the Trinity River Corridor Project.  The department maintains and operates the Dallas Floodwater System of pump stations, pressure sewers, levees, flood walls, drainage/closure structures, channels, floodway and miscellaneous facilities.  The Floodplain and Drainage Management Division provides studies and mapping to ensure that public infrastructure and private developments are designed to avoid flooding. Stormwater management educates the public on stormwater pollution prevention related issues and permitting requirements respective to protecting our creeks, lakes, and rivers to improve our lifestyle, natural environment, and water resource use. Finally, the Trinity River Corridor Project division oversees the economic development initiative of the Trinity River Vision plan.
Project Manager/Dept. Representative: Sirak Bahta, P.E.; Sr. Program Manager
 

City of Dallas Park & Recreation

Management of one of the nation's largest municipal park systems, with oversight of a $78 million operating budget and a capital budget in excess of $40 million annually. Capital Bond Program Development and Implementation, Facility and Site Development, Land Acquisition and Property Management, Infrastructure Maintenance and Construction, Environmental Management. Park & Recreation owns or operates: 380 parks, 13 lakes, 135 miles of trail, 41 recreation centers, skate attractions, nature preserves, dog parks. This department is also responsible for the management of Fair Park, the Dallas Zoo, Dallas Arboretum, and The Trinity River Audubon Center. 

 
 

City of Dallas Sanitation

Department Function: Provides programs and services that effectively and efficiently manage municipal solid waste generated within the City of Dallas. Sanitation Services operates and maintains the McCommas Bluff Landfill and 3 transfer stations.

description:
Please join us for our monthly D/FW OD Network Program
Thursday January 14 at  University of Dallas *
 
Please Register (above) for an accurate food count if you are coming!
More info:  http://dfwodnet.org/january2016meeting/  
   

 

Leadership BS:
Is the Leadership Development Industry Failing Us?

According to esteemed Stanford Organizational Behavior Professor Jeffrey Pfeffer, ". . . the continuing failure of the leadership industry in all of its forms and activities to make things better needs to be both explained and remedied."

Pfeffer adds that after 60 years and tens of billions of dollars, the leadership industry has produced worse leaders and organizations filled with dissatisfied, disengaged employees who do not trust those leaders.  Worse yet, he says the leadership industry is teaching exactly the opposite of what it should.

If you are reading this DFWOD Network solicitation, Pfeffer is speaking about you and me. Are we failing our clients? Have we failed the organizations that employ us? Have we failed those employees? Do we need to totally change what we do and how we do it?

Come listen to Randy Mayeux's synopsis of Professor Pfeffer's book, Leadership BS; Fixing Workplaces and Careers One Truth at a Time, and then join the discussion as Ed Savage facilitates an introspection of Pfeffer's writings and its impact on our leadership development activities.

Don’t miss this meeting. Your boss, leader, CEO, client may well be reading Pfeffer’s book and rethinking her work with you.

Presenter:   Randy Mayeux (First Friday Book Synopsis)

Facilitator:   Ed Savage  (L-3 Mission Integration)

We look forward to seeing you on January 14 at University of Dallas.  (We're back in the nice room we used in the first half of 2015!)

(Please join our LinkedIn Group if you haven't yet done so, and comment on the discussions.)   
   

 

Schedule for Thursday Evening:

   -  6:30  Networking / Food / Intros 
   -  7:15  Announcements / Program 
   -  8:45  Closing and evaluation  

 

 

Meeting Location:  University of Dallas - Catherine Hall, Room 11 * {New!} *

  1845 East Northgate Drive,    Irving, TX 75062     (972-721-5000)

  Catherine Hall is #20 on the UD Campus Map       [Google Map for Nav]
   >> Click for Satellite Map of the building and parking (with lat/long)
 
Note:  Catherine Hall is on the east end of the campus, just off Tom Braniff Drive (map).  Room 11 is on the first floor, just to the right of the front door.  (Much easier to find than our old room.)  
  
Parking:  Usually plenty of spaces in Lot P (map / map); also available in various places across the campus.
  
Cost:   No charge for members ($60/year).  $10 for guests. 
     

 

 

Speaker/Facilitator BIOs:  

Randy Mayeux is a professional speaker, educator, consultant, and writer. He gives more than 450 public presentations annually to various business and government audiences, non-profit groups and associations, and professional conferences. Randy is the Founder of Creative Communication Network, a full-service communication company offering speeches and presentations, training and custom consulting and meeting facilitation for individuals, groups and organizations.

His monthly First Friday Book Synopsis at the Dallas Park City Club now in its seventeenth year and attracts capacity crowds of business professionals from throughout the DFW metroplex.

He has authored articles in professional journals, guest columns in The Dallas Morning News, and several books. Randy is a graduate of Abilene Christian and Pepperdine University.

 

Ed Savage  is the Senior Manager of Training and Development for L-3 Mission Integration in Greenville. He has worked in the Leadership and Organization Development industry for 30 years. Ed holds a doctorate in Organization Change from Pepperdine University Graduate School of Education and Psychology.

      

 
  We look forward to seeing you there!
